@techreport{Scottish2002,
abstract = {On 8 March 2001, the Scottish Fisheries Minister announced to the Scottish Parliament that o1m would be made available for "a new partnership involving scientists and the fishing industry which will see fishing boats chartered to trial innovative gear to improve gear selectivity". As a result, the project became known as the Industry/Science Partnership. This was part of a much larger package worth o27m offering decommissioning and funding for the processing industry as well. The Industry/Science Partnership funds were administered through SEERAD and a Steering Committee involving the Scottish Fishermen's Federation, FRS Marine Laboratory, Seafish Industry Authority and the North Atlantic Fisheries College, as well as SEERAD, was set up to plan and carry out a range of projects. This report focuses on the projects to study the factors affecting selectivity and the assessment of the effect of more selective gears on catches and discards. A separate report describes projects aiming to improve knowledge of fish biology and distribution in Scottish waters. In addition to the gear work specifically funded through this initiative, the report also includes three other projects funded separately by SEERAD as part of the FRS annual programme in the years 2000 and 2001. The reason for including them here is that they are an integral part of the objectives to study the effect of square mesh panel position, a key issue in current technical conservation measures. A list of the gear trials reported in this document (Table 1) shows that there were 14 separate trips obtaining information on whitefish from 8 twin trawls, 2 Scottish seines, 2 single trawls, 1 pair seine and 1 pair trawl. Nephrops data were collected from 3 single trawls and 1 twin trawl. Nephrops and whitefish data were gathered from 2 dual purpose twin trawls. Individual reports from each vessel trip can be found in section 5. A summary of the key findings is found in section 4, grouped by topic - whitefish mesh size; whitefish panel position; whitefish multiple panels; Prawn mesh size; prawn panel position; prawn panel twine thickness; by-catch reduction in prawn trawls; extension length; towing speed; lifting bag; colour of netting; grids and panels. There are appendices explaining more detail of the experimental and analytical methods},
